#Text=John
#Text=May ( bishop )
#Text=John May ( Meye ) ( died 1598 ) was an English academic and churchman , who became bishop of Carlisle .
#Text=Life
#Text=He was a native of Suffolk and brother of William May .
#Text=He matriculated as a pensioner of Queens ' College , Cambridge , on 2 May 1544 .
#Text=He was appointed bible-clerk of his college , and in 1550 proceeded B.A. , being elected fellow in 1550 . [ 1 ]
#Text=He commenced M.A. in 1553 , and acted as bursar of the college during 1553 , 1554 , and 1555 .
#Text=Queens ' was split in religious sympathies in the Marian period , and May belonged to the Catholic group rather than the reformers . [ 2 ]

#Text=At midsummer 1557 , he was ordained priest , and on 16 November following he was instituted to the rectory of Aston Sandford , Buckinghamshire , owned by Edward de Vere , [ 3 ] resigning in 1558 .
#Text=In 1559 he was elected to the mastership of Catharine Hall , Cambridge .
#Text=In 1560 he commenced B.D. , and was collated to the rectory of Long Stanton St. Michael , Cambridgeshire .
#Text=In 1562 Archbishop Matthew Parker collated him to the rectory of North Creake , Norfolk ; and he held also the moiety of the rectory of Darfield , Yorkshire .
#Text=About 1564 he obtained a canonry of Ely , which he held until May 1582 .
#Text=Also , in 1564 he was created D.D.
#Text=In 1565 he was nominated one of the Lent preachers at court .
#Text=On 26 September in that year he was collated by Archbishop Parker to the rectory of St. Dunstan-in-the East , London , which he vacated in January 1574 .
#Text=He was admitted to the archdeaconry of the East Riding of Yorkshire by proxy on 3 August 1569 , in person on 8 October 1571 , and retained it until the end of 1588 .

#Text=He served the office of vice-chancellor of the University of Cambridge for the year from November 1569 , and was in a commission to visit King 's College , Cambridge , in a state of confusion over the conduct of Dr. Philip Baker , the Provost .
#Text=Through the influence of George Talbot , 6th Earl of Shrewsbury , May was raised to the see of Carlisle , being consecrated on 29 September 1577 .
#Text=He obtained the Queen 's licence to hold his other preferments in commendam , but had long-term financial troubles .
#Text=From his correspondence with Shrewsbury , he appears to have taken a serious interest in Scottish affairs .

#Text=On 15 February 1593 , the Queen presented William Holland to the rectory of North Creake , which May still held , and there arose a suit in the Queen 's bench ; it was held that the rectory might be treated as void by reason of May having been subsequently inducted to Darfield .
#Text=May died at Rose Castle on 15 February 1598 , being about seventy years of age .
#Text=He was buried at Carlisle , according to the parish register of Dalston , Cumbria , a few hours after his death , which was probably caused by the plague .
#Text=Works
#Text=May wrote some plays , now lost , which were acted by the members of Queens ' College in 1551 and 1553 .
#Text=He was concerned in the compilation of the statutes given to the university by Elizabeth in 1570 .
#Text=Among the Tanner manuscripts in the Bodleian Library are some notes of a sermon which he preached at Paul 's Cross in 1565 .
#Text=Family
#Text=His wife was Amy , daughter of William Vowel of Creake Abbey , Norfolk , and widow of John Cowel of Lancashire .

#Text=By her he had issue : John of Shouldham , Norfolk , who married Cordelia , daughter of Martin Bowes of Norfolk ; Elizabeth , wife of Richard Bird , D.D. ; Alice , wife of Richard Burton of Burton , Yorkshire ; and Anne , wife of Richard Pilkington , D.D. , rector of Hambleden , Buckinghamshire .
